#registry GUI; // this is old plg syntax
<simple window x=300 y=450 width=400 height=200 rounded>
    <third pad=5 fill=wall across>
        <wrap fill=white>
            <one text pad=5 border=off register>This is a whole lot of text that I am using to test out text views, scrolling, and isn't it nice that the xcode text editor wraps lines and indents auto-magically. The base rule is you have to specify everything you want, nothing implied except styles are inherited.</wrap>
        <two fill=red left=2/>
        <three fill=white width=50.0% left=2>
            <stuff text=one pad=5 border=off/></third>
    <fourth rounded pad fill=lightGreen onLayout>
        print "Ran the onLayout method":;</simple>

The incant version in define format
registry(GUI);
define
simple window x=300 y=450 width=400 height=200 rounded
    third pad=5 fill=wall across
        wrap fill=white
            one="This is a whole lot of text that I am using to test out text views, scrolling, and isn't it nice that the xcode text editor wraps lines and indents auto-magically. The base rule is you have to specify everything you want, nothing implied except styles are inherited." text pad=5 border=off register;
        two fill=red left=2;
        three fill=white width=50.0% left=2
            stuff text=one pad=5 border=off;
    fourth rounded pad fill=lightGreen onLayout; {
        print "Ran the onLayout method":; };
;

Note I may not have the right number of ending ; This is one area where I like the xml ending better. The bit </simple> closes out all blocks above it. Need multiple ;;; to do that in incant. Maybe we should steal the block ending approach from the old plg specification
